            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/51581",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "If you are going to use the DSN to pass some parameters, you need to utilize the php.net parameter names for mysql:\r\nhttp:\/\/us2.php.net\/manual\/en\/ref.pdo-mysql.php\r\n\r\nIn your example, you're using 'hostname' instead of 'host'.  Zend\\Db will not attempt to rewrite your DSN.\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you can use the connection abstraction in ZF2:\r\nhttp:\/\/packages.zendframework.com\/docs\/latest\/manual\/en\/modules\/zend.db.adapter.html\r\n\r\nMine looks like this:\r\n\r\n{code}\r\n$dbconfig = array(\r\n    'driver' => 'Pdo Mysql',\r\n    'hostname' => 'some.remote.com',\r\n    'database' => 'zend_db_example',\r\n    'username' => 'developer',\r\n    'password' => 'developer'\r\n);\r\n{code}\r\n  ",
